The losers remain challengers
HARARE: Before this month's presidential elections, I was convinced that irregularities in the elections would have serious consequences for Zimbabwe itself and the entire southern Africa region.
Despite the shadows of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe did not get them.
Instead, they received terror.
In the two years leading up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe were victims of intimidation, harassment, and threats by the party of Robert Mugabe, the African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-subsidized terrorism.
The ZANU terror is attributed to the thugs among the veterans from Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, government militias, and young men who are all supported by the police.
The result of intimidation and violence was that my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), did not reach the electorate in large parts, especially in rural areas.
Moreover, my opponent's government, President Mugabe's, effectively disenfranchised hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
Since there were not enough polling stations overall, in my opinion, more than 360,000 people had to stand in line alone in Harare and Chitungwiza without being able to cast their ballot into the urn.
I continue to question the legitimacy of the election result because Mugabe's militias prevented the MDC observers from being present at 52% of rural polling stations.
By the end of the voting, our party observers were missing from 6 out of 10 polling stations in the countryside.
This means that Mugabe's supporters could impose their will in these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all polling stations that were controlled only by ZANU supporters.
In our preliminary investigations, even at this early stage, a pattern has emerged: in these polling stations, most votes went to Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the result of the presidential elections, in which the incumbent president Robert Mugabe emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million cast votes.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the Zimbabwean people and is considered illegitimate in their eyes.
The people of Zimbabwe were denied their right to freely and democratically elect a president.
The fight over the election results is a political issue that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation stands at over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and determined, and they deserve to have this acknowledged.
Perhaps it is not too late for that.
I write these words in sorrow, because Mugabe's regime still ignores the will of the people.
No matter what happens, I will stand as a loyal servant to the people and walk the path with them to the end.
The government might want to arrest me.
I was also arrested for high treason before the elections.
In the worst case, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never be able to break the will of the people, their rights, and their power.
It is up to us to effect a democratic change.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow despair to overcome us.
The political change is irreversible.
But we must be ready to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen fear the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger.
If it comes to that, I only ask the people of Zimbabwe to stay strong and finish what we have started together.
There are many heroes among the people of Zimbabwe – heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who did not give up.
It are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe whose voice must be heard in the world.
We have walked a very steep path together to achieve democratic change in our country.
In the history of mankind, a people has rarely had to endure such violence and yet manage to preserve charm and excessiveness.
I notice that the population of Zimbabwe is impatient.
I understand that.
But for there to be a political process, they must be patient and wait.
They cannot simply let these elections pass, but they must also not fall for Mugabe's provocations and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want change, in the constitution, in the legal system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not alone.
We know that elections are rigged all over Africa.
In most African countries, irregularities, fraud, and deceit seem to be par for the course in elections.
There is always some kind of crisis over elections somewhere in Africa.
It is sad, but the entire continent is plagued by governments that resort to unfair means when it comes time to grant people their right to vote.
But those who want something different can hope.
Zimbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
There is still time to draw lessons for Africa and the world from our experience.
My people are in the hour of their greatest need.
I vow not to leave them.
